{"id":14881412,"mediaExerciseId":"0f574367-d4b5-4887-b238-b41645e93fa4","exerciseName":"13","chapterName":"13","chapterTitle":"Return, Risk, and The Security Market Line","groupId":612376,"groupTitle":"Questions and Problems","isPremium":true,"sectionName":null,"sectionTitle":null,"pageNumber":453,"solutions":[{"id":5997245,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"In this exercise, we are asked to determine the stock's expected return using CAPM. ","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":61,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/09/6bc9882a3145cde999b3b46a3bd4009d/17b9612b1d4f6c841b63ffe9adcdb5a7/lateximg_large.png","width":997},"regular":{"height":32,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/09/6bc9882a3145cde999b3b46a3bd4009d/17b9612b1d4f6c841b63ffe9adcdb5a7/lateximg.png","width":497}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"The **capital asset pricing model (CAPM)** is an equation that shows how systematic risk and expected returns are related. The CAPM informs us that the expected return is influenced by the time value of money, theÂ risk premium, and the stock's beta compared to an average value.\n","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":143,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/09/6bc9882a3145cde999b3b46a3bd4009d/596742374580d84f620bed5939233f33/lateximg_large.png","width":996},"regular":{"height":72,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/09/6bc9882a3145cde999b3b46a3bd4009d/596742374580d84f620bed5939233f33/lateximg.png","width":498}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":2},{"columns":[{"text":"Let's first identify the given amounts in the problem: \n\n\n| | Amount$\\hspace{5pt}$| \n|:--|--:| \n|Beta |1.15|\n|Market expected return |10.3\\%|\n|Risk-free rate| 3.1\\%|","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":99,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/09/6bc9882a3145cde999b3b46a3bd4009d/9729b8d318518a964c5eb5ee3c0a11cb/lateximg_large.png","width":997},"regular":{"height":51,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/09/6bc9882a3145cde999b3b46a3bd4009d/9729b8d318518a964c5eb5ee3c0a11cb/lateximg.png","width":499}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":3},{"columns":[{"text":"The capital asset pricing model (CAPM) is as follows: \n\n$$\\begin{aligned}\n\\text{r }_{I}&={\\text{R}_{f}} + {{[B}_{I}}{\\text{ $\\times$ }}{\\text{(R}_{m}} - {\\text{R}_{f}}{)]}\n\\end{aligned}$$\n\nWhere: \n$$\\begin{aligned}\n{\\text{r}_{I}}& = {\\text{Cost of capital for an investment}} \\\\\n{\\text{R}_{f}}& = {\\text{Risk-free interest rate }} \\\\\n{\\text{R}_{m}}& = {\\text{Market expected return  }} \\\\\n{\\text{B}_{I}} &= {\\text{Beta}} \n\\end{aligned}$$","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":326,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/09/6bc9882a3145cde999b3b46a3bd4009d/c03d931f636ac90e5e2bef97eb59ebc0/lateximg_large.png","width":759},"regular":{"height":164,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/09/6bc9882a3145cde999b3b46a3bd4009d/c03d931f636ac90e5e2bef97eb59ebc0/lateximg.png","width":378}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":4},{"columns":[{"text":"First, let us insert the provided data to the formula from step 4. As an illustration, here's what it looks like: \n\n\n$$\\begin{aligned}\n\\text{r }_{I}&={\\text{3.1\\%}} + {{[1.15}}{\\text{ $\\times$ }}{\\text{(10.3\\%}} - {\\text{3.1\\%}}{)]}\n\\end{aligned}$$","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":144,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/09/6bc9882a3145cde999b3b46a3bd4009d/1405baaf9ebe0ece57c65602f9517244/lateximg_large.png","width":996},"regular":{"height":73,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/09/6bc9882a3145cde999b3b46a3bd4009d/1405baaf9ebe0ece57c65602f9517244/lateximg.png","width":499}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":5},{"columns":[{"text":"Now, let us compute the expected return. This is computed as follows: \n\n$$\\begin{aligned}\n\\text{r }_{I}&={\\text{3.1\\%}} + {{[1.15}}{\\text{ $\\times$ }}{\\text{(10.3\\%}} - {\\text{3.1\\%}}{)]}\\\\\n&={\\text{3.1\\%}} + {{(1.15}}{\\text{ $\\times$ }}{\\text{7.2\\%}}{)}\\\\\n&={\\text{3.1\\%}} + {{8.28\\%}}\\\\\n&={\\textbf{11.38\\%}}\n\\end{aligned}$$","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":230,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/09/6bc9882a3145cde999b3b46a3bd4009d/5a2091d849decd8afa122066c9818a8e/lateximg_large.png","width":938},"regular":{"height":116,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/09/6bc9882a3145cde999b3b46a3bd4009d/5a2091d849decd8afa122066c9818a8e/lateximg.png","width":469}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":6},{"columns":[{"text":"**To conclude, the expected return of the stock is 11.38%.**","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":7}],"rating":5,"solutionUuid":"9a250571-8836-4068-967a-acabbb3a8675","editorVersion":2,"answeredOn":null,"ratingCount":null,"solutionOrder":null,"totalSteps":7}],"textbook":{"authors":"Bradford D. Jordan, Randolph W. Westerfield, Stephen A. Ross","imageUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/textbook_covers/tmpm0p82b7h","imageThumbnailUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/cache/d1/d3/d1d34d106dd29dd2e71be582412ef59d.jpg","id":34320,"isbn":"9781259918957","isPremium":true,"title":"Fundamentals of Corporate Finance","edition":"12th Edition","verifiedSolutionCount":1217,"shouldBeIndexableForSeo":true,"modified":1665448474394,"active":true,"publisher":"McGraw-Hill Education","mainTextbookIsbn":null,"subjects":{"level1":["Social Science"],"level2":["Economics"],"level3":["Finance"]}},"nextExercises":[{"id":14881413,"exercise